                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d676">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/9389: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-08-17T19:00:00-04:00"
                            >August 17, 1937—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>241. Your 487, August 15, 3 p.m. Department is of the opinion that activities of
                    the American citizens described in first paragraph of your telegram reasonably
                    come within the purview of Section 4090 of the Revised Statutes and may be
                    prohibited by the United States Court for China pursuant to authority conferred
                    on the Court by Section 1 of the Act of June 30, 1906.<note n="5"
                        xml:id="d676fn5">34 Stat 814.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Williamson and other American citizens concerned should be so advised.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
